# Calorie AI — core context

## Stack

- **Ruby** 4.x (see `.ruby-version`), **Rails** ~8.1, **PostgreSQL**
- **Hotwire**: Turbo + Stimulus; **importmap-rails** (no `package.json` / npm workflow for app JavaScript)
- **Assets**: Propshaft, **Tailwind** via `tailwindcss-rails` (source under `app/assets/tailwind/`)
- **Infra in-app**: Solid Cache / Queue / Cable;

## Where things live

| Area | Paths |
|------|--------|
| HTTP | `app/controllers/`, `config/routes.rb` |
| Domain logic | `app/models/`, `app/services/` (if present) |
| UI | `app/views/`, `app/helpers/` |
| JS behavior | `app/javascript/controllers/` |
| Styles | `app/assets/tailwind/application.css`, built CSS in `app/assets/builds/` |
| DB | `db/migrate/`, `db/schema.rb` |
| Tests | `test/` (Minitest), system tests with Capybara |

## Quality gate

Prefer matching what CI enforces: `bin/rubocop`, `bin/rails test` (and `test:system` when UI changes), `bin/brakeman`, `bin/bundler-audit`, `bin/importmap audit`. Local aggregate: `bin/ci` (see `config/ci.rb`).

**Style**: `rubocop-rails-omakase` via `.rubocop.yml` — follow it unless the team explicitly changes config.

## Design defaults

- Prefer **Sandi Metz–style OO** for domain behavior (small objects, message passing, composition and polymorphism over sprawling conditionals). For ActiveRecord boundaries, **lean on Rails** (validations, enums, scopes, associations, `delegate`) before inventing parallel patterns—see `backend-rails.mdc`.

## Editing norms

- Keep changes scoped to the request; avoid drive-by refactors and unrelated files.
- Do not commit secrets; use env / credentials patterns already in the app (`dotenv-rails` in Gemfile for dev/test).
